---

<Layout>
  <div class="container my-4">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-10">
        <a href="/courses/foce/" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-light mb-3">
          <i class="si-arrow-left"></i> Back
        </a>

        <h1>Activity 1.10: If Statements</h1>
        <Divider variant="8" classes="mb-5" />

        <!-- Launch / Concept -->
        <section id="launch">
          <Presentation>
            <section>
              <h2>Activity 1.10</h2>
              <h3 class="text-sn-theme">If Statements</h3>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Key Concepts</h2>
              <p>The if Statement</p>
              <p>Code Blocks</p>
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate>
              <h2>The if Statement</h2>
              <p>
                An <b class="text-sn-theme">if statement</b> runs a block of
                code only when its condition is <code>True</code>.
              </p>
              <Code code={Figure1} frame="code" lang="python" showLineNumbers={false} />
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate data-auto-animate-restart>
              <h2>Indentation Defines the Block</h2>
              <p>
                Python doesn't use curly braces to mark a code block &mdash;
                it uses a colon and <b>indentation</b>. Every indented line
                right after the <code>if</code> belongs to it.
              </p>
              <Code code={Figure2} frame="code" lang="python" showLineNumbers={false} />
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate>
              <h2>Only Runs When True</h2>
              <Code code={Figure3} frame="terminal" lang="txt" showLineNumbers={false} />
              <Code code={Figure4} frame="terminal" lang="txt" showLineNumbers={false} class="mt-2" />
            </section>

            <section data-auto-animate data-auto-animate-restart>
              <h2>Multiple Independent Checks</h2>
              <p>
                You can write several <code>if</code> statements in a row
                &mdash; each one is checked independently, so more than one
                can run.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Today's Objectives</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Writing an <code>if</code> statement</li>
                <li>Using indentation to define a code block</li>
                <li>Writing several independent <code>if</code> checks in one program</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section>
              <h2>Key Terms</h2>
              <div class="text-start">
                <dl>
                  <dt>if Statement</dt>
                  <dd>Runs a block of code only when its condition is <code>True</code>.</dd>
                  <dt>Condition</dt>
                  <dd>The boolean expression an <code>if</code> statement checks.</dd>
                  <dt>Code Block</dt>
                  <dd>A group of statements, marked in Python by indentation.</dd>
                </dl>
              </div>
            </section>
          </Presentation>
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Build -->
        <section id="build">
          <h2>Build</h2>

          <p>
            Create a new Python script named <b class="text-sn-theme">1-10-if-statements.py</b>.
          </p>

          <hr class="my-4" />

          <h3>Task 1: Age Validator</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Check the user's age against three independent milestones (16, 18, 35).</li>
          </ul>

          <Code code={Task1} frame="code" lang="python" title="1-10-if-statements.py" mark="5-6,8-10,12-18" />

          <hr class="my-4" />

          <h3>Task 2: Simple Score Calculator</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Check whether a score of 0-100 passes or fails.</li>
          </ul>

          <Code code={Task2} frame="code" lang="python" title="1-10-if-statements.py" mark="26-27,29-30" ins="22-32" />

          <hr class="my-4" />

          <h3>Task 3: Temperature Check</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Check a Fahrenheit temperature against three ranges, using <code>and</code> for the middle range.</li>
          </ul>

          <Code code={Task3} frame="code" lang="python" title="1-10-if-statements.py" mark="42-43" ins="34-48" />

          <hr class="my-4" />

          <h3>Task 4: Letter Grade Calculator</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Check a grade percentage against five independent letter-grade ranges.</li>
          </ul>

          <Code code={Task4} frame="code" lang="python" title="1-10-if-statements.py" mark="54-63" ins="50-63" />
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Checkpoint -->
        <section id="checkpoint">
          <h2>Checkpoint</h2>

          <p>Verify your program works correctly.</p>

          <Code
            code={SampleOutput}
            frame="terminal"
            lang="txt"
            showLineNumbers={false}
            title="Example Output"
          />
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Reflection -->
        <section id="reflection">
          <h2>Reflection</h2>

          <p>Answer the following questions before submitting your work.</p>

          <ol>
            <li>How does Python know which lines belong inside an <code>if</code> statement's block?</li>
            <li>In the Letter Grade Calculator, why does each range (like the B range) need two conditions joined by <code>and</code>?</li>
            <li>What would happen to the Age Validator if you entered an age of 10? Which messages, if any, would print?</li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="my-5" />

        <!-- Submit -->
        <section id="submit">
          <h2>Submit</h2>

          <p>Submit the required files to the appropriate dropbox.</p>

          <h1
            class="text-center mt-5 text-sn-theme border border-primary slow-flash"
          >
            Activity Complete
          </h1>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
